NAME
    RT-Extension-QueueListCustom - Customisable queue list portlet for the
    RT homepage

DESCRIPTION
    This extension adds a homepage portlet called *Queue list by lifecycle
    (custom)* that replaces RT's built-in Queue list portlet with a fully
    per-user configurable version.

  Features
    *   Per-lifecycle status columns -- choose exactly which ticket statuses
        appear as columns for each lifecycle. Defaults to "initial" and
        "active".

    *   Per-lifecycle queue visibility -- hide individual queues you do not
        care about. Hidden queues are only hidden for you and do not affect
        other users.

    *   Configurable empty-queue hiding -- queues with zero tickets across
        all visible status columns are hidden automatically by default.
        Users can enable Show empty queues in the preferences to always show
        all queues.

    *   Collapsible lifecycle sections -- each lifecycle section can be
        individually collapsed. The collapsed state is saved and restored on
        the next page load.

    *   Drag-and-drop lifecycle ordering -- reorder lifecycle sections on
        the preferences page by dragging the handle icon. The order is saved
        per user.

    *   Manual reload -- a reload button in the portlet header fetches fresh
        ticket counts without reloading the whole page.

    *   Last loaded timestamp -- shows when the ticket counts were last
        fetched, so you always know how current the data is.

    *   Configurable auto-refresh -- optionally refresh the portlet
        automatically every 2, 5, 10, 20, 60 or 120 minutes.

    Only lifecycles belonging to queues the current user has "SeeQueue"
    access to are shown, both in the portlet and on the preferences page.
    Users in different roles therefore see different lifecycle and queue
    combinations automatically. Ticket counts respect "ShowTicket" — queues
    where the user cannot see any tickets will show zeros and are hidden
    automatically by the empty-queue filter.

RT VERSION
    Works with RT 6.0.

INSTALLATION
    "perl Makefile.PL"
    "make"
    "make install"
        May need root permissions.

    Edit /opt/rt6/etc/RT_SiteConfig.pm
        Add the plugin:

            Plugin('RT::Extension::QueueListCustom');

        Add "QueueListCustom" to your $HomepageComponents list so users can
        add the portlet to their homepage:

            Set($HomepageComponents, [qw(
                ... your existing components ...
                QueueListCustom
            )]);

    Clear your mason cache
            rm -rf /opt/rt6/var/mason_data/obj

    Restart your webserver

USAGE
  Add the portlet to your homepage
    Go to your RT homepage, click Edit, find QueueListCustom in the left
    panel under *Component*, and drag it into the Body or Summary column.
    Click Save to confirm.

  Portlet header icons
    The portlet title bar has two icons on the right:

    Reload (arrow icon) -- fetches fresh ticket counts via AJAX without
    reloading the page. Also resets the auto-refresh timer if configured.
    Edit (gear icon) -- opens the preferences page.

    The bottom of the portlet shows when the ticket counts were last loaded
    and, if auto-refresh is active, how often they are refreshed.

  Preferences page
    Open the preferences page via the gear icon or directly at
    /Prefs/QueueListStatuses.html.

   General settings
    Auto-refresh interval -- select how often the portlet should refresh
    automatically: *Off* (default), or every 2, 5, 10, 20, 60 or 120
    minutes.

    Show empty queues -- when enabled, queues with no tickets in the
    selected status columns are shown anyway. By default they are hidden
    automatically.

   Per-lifecycle settings
    Each lifecycle you have access to appears as a card. Drag the handle
    icon on the left of the card header to reorder lifecycles.

    Within each card you can:

    Status columns -- check the statuses you want to appear as columns.
    Statuses are grouped by category (*initial*, *active*, *inactive*) with
    labels so you can see at a glance what each status means. Use *Select
    all*, *Deselect all* or *Reset to defaults* to quickly adjust the
    selection. Defaults are the "initial" and "active" statuses of the
    lifecycle.
    Visible queues -- uncheck queues you want to hide. All queues are
    visible by default.
    Start collapsed -- check this to have the lifecycle section start folded
    up in the portlet.

    Click Save Changes to apply — the button appears both at the top and
    bottom of the page. If you make any changes, an Unsaved changes
    indicator appears next to the top button as a reminder. All settings are
    stored per user and do not affect other users.

CONFIGURATION
    No server-side configuration is required beyond the Plugin() call and
    $HomepageComponents entry described under "INSTALLATION". All portlet
    behaviour is configured per user via the preferences page.

